	<div id="id1bfa" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Name calling" width="171" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/b0a72ec6"/><span class="title">Name calling</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on September 4, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id1bfb" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../city/tag/politics/#selected-tag"><span>politics</span></a><span id="id1bfc">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/language/#selected-tag"><span>language</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>Consider the following banned from intelligent (political) conversation:</p>


	<p style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/wingnut.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<ul>
	<li>wingnut</li>
		<li>moonbat</li>
		<li>dingbat</li>
		<li>netnut</li>
		<li>wingbat</li>
	</ul>


	<p>First you must accept that none of these are, under any circumstances, clever. Not even &#8220;wingnut.&#8221; Especially not &#8220;wingnut,&#8221; which probably started this whole idiotic trend. Sure, it&#8217;s great that there&#8217;s a piece of hardware whose name you can decompose into a reference to the <em>Assembl√©e nationale</em> and, like, an insane person. That&#8217;s so funny!</p>


	<p>But I&#8217;m sick and tired of reading otherwise intelligent political commentary and thinking, &#8220;right on, maaaan,&#8221; and then the poster starts talking about what the loonies, etc, on the other side are doing.</p>


	<p>These schoolhouse jeers can easily be applied in any political direction. How do the left/right bloggers keep it straight? What happens if Rush Limbaugh calls someone a &#8220;wingnut?&#8221; Do his listeners&#8217; SUVs explode?</p>


	<p>Like, grow up, people.</p></div>
